    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Perennial low-lying shrub consisting of densely-entangled stems emerging from a woody underground rhizome and scrambling over rocks or other vegetation. The large blue-green leaves have rolled-under sides and have several lateral projections, each bearing a terminal spine, plus another spine at the tip. Young leaves are covered in cottony white hairs, but these wear off the upper surface as the leaves mature, revealing a glossy surface.</p><p>The compound flowers are borne on lateral branches and resemble pincushion proteas, with a group of tubular florets surrounded by spiny bracts.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10248",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Can reach a height of 80 cm, but typically much lower (25 cm) and spreading to at least 1 m across, leaves up to 100 mm long and flowers about 10 mm diameter.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10249",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa. Naturalised in Australia.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Broad coastal band from about Saldanha Bay to about Mossel Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10250",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Occurs mostly on rocky areas in a broad coastal band, but also in deep sand or hanging from cliffs. Resprouts readily from rootstock after fires and is one of the first plants to flower after fire.</p><p>Unpalatable to grazers due to its spiny leaves. Has been accidentally introduced to Australia where it is regarded as a minor pest when it becomes common in grasslands, as it limits grazing and access.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10251",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10252",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers September to January. Pollinated by bees, flies and monkey beetles. The seeds remain in the flowerhead and are dispersed when this is which rolled or dispersed by the wind.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10253",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>A diverse genus with about 75 South African species characterised by their lobed and spiny leaves and usually yellow compound flowers. The closely related Coast thistle <i>B. barbata</i> has similar distribution and leaves but the flowers are large, flat, yellow daisies more like small sunflowers.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10254",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 406).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10255",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
